Instead, news were on..half awake, I watch thinking they start the show late. Switching channels, I see the same everywhere and settle down to watch..<br>
Realizing what happened, I don't know what I thought or felt. A dream? A joke? Disbelief. Denial. Shock. Not even anger at this moment. I was numbed and stunned..glued to the screen for I don't know how long.<br>
<br>
Shaking this off, I race to my comp. My icq is a blinking xmas tree mess.<br>
I'm in luck, I find one of my NY friends online. Nothing happened to him, but he had a first-row seat having his office near the crumbling towers. But all the normal phonelines are dead. I offer him to call his wife.<br>
<br>
In the end, I'm in luck. No one I know died there. But none of that helped. I felt like I was sleepwalking in a bad dream for a couple days.<br>
Its still irritating to think back, or to watch the pictures on TV again.<br>
<br>
My first thought of anger was &quot;screw those fucks, drop nukes to the whole darn place&quot;. At that time I didn't care/realize that it wouldn't be any better and kill tons of innocents. Vengeance, in the worst way.<br>
<br>
I remember having to turn the TV off after the 3rd day of straight news reporting only..I didn't want to hear it anymore. I needed some calm to just relax and take my mind off this whole thing. I'm reminded every day, and although I could live without memory, I don't want to forget the lives this cost.<br>
<br>
I'm normally pretty cold, I didn't think anything much I could see would still shock me considering all the stuff that already happens in this world, but this event did. And while I realize its very unlikely to happen, I'll down some good drinks whenever I see Osama's head severed from his body in the most painful way mankind can imagine. <p><p><font color="red">Baron Rugal Bloodwind<br><font color="6F6F6F">
